tinuatus was intended to justify the murderous accession of Basil I (867-886), grandfather of Constantine VII and founder of the Macedonian dynasty, by presenting the emperors who preceded Basil as cruel heretics (Leo V, Michael II, Theophilus) or profligates (Michael III). But the facts here recorded and the often playful use of Classical learning give proof to the careful reader that the revival of Byzantine military power and culture from the Dark Age of the seventh and eighth centuries gained momentum under these same emperors. The present critical edition of Books I-IV replaces that of 1838 by I. Bekker. Accompanied by the first complete English translation and grammatical and historical indexes, the work is intended for specialists, students, and scholars in related fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Greek, Modern (1453-).0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEmperorszByzantine EmpirevBiography. 4aByzantine historiography. 4aByzanz. 4aConstantine Porphyrogenitus. 4aIconoclasm. 4aKonstantin Porphyrogenitos. 4aTheophanes Continuatus. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aFeatherstone, Jeffrey Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSignes-Codoñer, Juan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2015z9783110438604oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97816145195910 cprintz978161451598240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161451504340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781614515043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781614515043.jpg  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_H